{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ad589786-c65e-4d63-bea9-67be4dadc26e","content":"There's no project at that path yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### User install\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWant me to scaffold the project with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f0b43687-040c-47bc-87b2-9adc2b87f47c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory doesn't exist yet. The user is asking what they need to configure, not asking me to do it. Let me give them guidance on what's needed to publish a C# MCP server as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org.","outputTokens":501,"requestId":"CBC7:22220D:17FC20E:1B47D70:69FE8A06"},"id":"8ba8ee13-212e-40d2-a7a2-69ea7f430830","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:12:47.269Z","parentId":"c008744c-393f-47c6-abb3-5c5830234726"}
